EXPERIMENT- 1.1 CONTAIN DUPLICATE (LEETCODE PROBLEM 217)

1) AIM:- Given an integer array nums, return true if any value appears at least twice in the array, and return false if every element is distinct.

2) ALGORITHM:-
1. Sort the given array nums in ascending order.
2. Traverse the array from the second element (i = 1) to the last element.
3. Compare the current element nums[i] with the previous element nums[i-1].
4. If both elements are equal, a duplicate exists, so return true.
5. If the loop finishes without finding equal adjacent elements, return false.

3) CODE:-
class Solution {
public:
    bool containsDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {
        sort(nums.begin(),nums.end());
        for(int i=1;i<nums.size();i++){
            if(nums[i]==nums[i-1]){
                return true;
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
};

EXPERIMENT- 1.2 CONTAIN DUPLICATE 2 (LEETCODE PROBLEM 219)

1) AIM:-Given an integer array nums and an integer k, return true if there are two distinct indices i and j in the array such that nums[i] == nums[j] and abs(i - j) <= k.

2) ALGORITHM:- 
1. Create an unordered map mp to store each number and its latest index.
2. Traverse the array from left to right using index i.
3. For every element nums[i]:
       A) Check whether nums[i] already exists in the map.
       B) If it exists, calculate the distance between the current index and its previous index:
abs(i - mp[nums[i]])
       C) If this distance is less than or equal to k, return true.
4. Update the map with the current element and its current index:
mp[nums[i]] = i
5. If the complete array is traversed without finding a nearby duplicate, return false.

3) CODE:- 
class Solution {
public:
    bool containsNearbyDuplicate(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        unordered_map<int,int> mp;
        for(int i=0;i<nums.size();i++){
            if(mp.find(nums[i])!=mp.end() && abs(i-mp[nums[i]])<=k){
                return true;
            }
        mp[nums[i]]=i;
            
        }
        return false;
    }
